I found it interesting that a black preacher, named Rev. R. D. Cobbs, thought lynching was what people of his own color deserved and he explicitly stated it in the papers. Cobbs was an ex- slave and freedman who lived in the South since the war. He felt blacks deserved lynching because of the "brutal outrage on the wives and daughters of white people," and he felt Ida B. Wells should inform the North that this is why blacks are being lynched in the South. The reverend also stated that white men of the South are "liberal and kindhearted," who wanted what was best for blacks. I also found it interesting that when the reverend spoke about Ida B. Wells, he said "let her come among her own people in the South." Are Ida B. Wells people not also his own people? Aren't they all of the same color? Then they should certainly also be his people. I wonder if there is an agenda at play here. Was the reverend forced to make this statement? because no one in their right mind should say such a thing, or was there no agenda at play? If there isn't an agenda at play, then it shows that there were possibly many others like the reverend who turned their backs on their own people.
